3 (d) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, in ruling on a petition for
4 guardianship of a child, a juvenile court shall give primary consideration to the health and
5 safety of the child and consideration to all other factors needed to determine whether
6 terminating a parent’s rights is in the child’s best interests, including:
7 (1) (i) all services offered to the parent before the child’s placement,
8 whether offered by a local department, another agency, or a professional;
9 (ii) the extent, nature, and timeliness of services offered by a local
10 department to facilitate reunion of the child and parent; and
11 (iii) the extent to which a local department and parent have fulfilled
12 their obligations under a social services agreement, if any;
13 (2) the results of the parent’s effort to adjust the parent’s circumstances,
14 condition, or conduct to make it in the child’s best interests for the child to be returned to
15 the parent’s home, including:
16 (i) the extent to which the parent has maintained regular contact
17 with:
18 1. the child;
19 2. the local department to which the child is committed; and
20 3. if feasible, the child’s caregiver;
21 (ii) the parent’s contribution to a reasonable part of the child’s care
22 and support, if the parent is financially able to do so;
23 (iii) the existence of a parental disability that makes the parent
24 consistently unable to care for the child’s immediate and ongoing physical or psychological
25 needs for long periods of time; and
26 (iv) whether additional services would be likely to bring about a
27 lasting parental adjustment so that the child could be returned to the parent within an
28 ascertainable time not to exceed 18 months from the date of placement unless the juvenile
29 court makes a specific finding that it is in the child’s best interests to extend the time for a
30 specified period;
31 (3) whether:

